# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: virtual-file-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] FUSE is available for Linux, FreeBSD, OpenBSD, NetBSD (as puffs), OpenSolaris, Minix 3, macOS, MorphOS (as filesysbox.library), and Windows.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] FUSE is free software originally released under the terms of the GNU General Public License and the GNU Lesser General Public License.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] Plan 9 users have a ftpfs command that will connect to a ftp server, populate remote files in their name space, and translate 9p operations into ftp operations.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] This allows standard utilities (grep, sed, etc.) to work directly on remote files.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] Since then, several implementations of ftpfs and sshfs have appeared.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The FUSE system was originally part of *AVFS* (*A Virtual Filesystem*), a filesystem implementation heavily influenced by the translator concept of the GNU Hurd.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] It superseded Linux Userland Filesystem, and provided a translational interface using `lufis` in libfuse1.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] FUSE was originally released under the terms of the GNU General Public License and the GNU Lesser General Public License, later also reimplemented as part of the FreeBSD base system and released under the terms of Simplified BSD license.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] An ISC-licensed re-implementation by Sylvestre Gallon was released in March 2013, and incorporated into OpenBSD in June 2013.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The userspace side of FUSE, the libfuse library, generally followed the pace of Linux kernel development while maintaining "best effort" compatibility with BSD descendants.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] This is possible because the kernel FUSE reports its own "feature levels", or versions.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The exception is the FUSE fork for macOS, OSXFUSE, which has too many differences for sharing a library.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] A break in libfuse history is libfuse3, which includes some incompatible improvements in the interface and performance, compared to the older libfuse2 now under maintenance mode.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] As the kernel-userspace protocol of FUSE is versioned and public, a programmer can choose to use a different piece of code in place of libfuse and still communicate with the kernel's FUSE facilities.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] On the other hand, libfuse and its many ports provide a portable high-level interface that may be implemented on a system without a "FUSE" facility.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The version of FUSE for Mac OS X has too many differences for sharing the same library as regular libfuse systems.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] It was started as Google's MacFUSE in 2009 and forked as OSXFUSE in 2011 by Benjamin Fleischer.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] OSXFUSE was rebranded as macFUSE in 2020 following the rebrand of Mac OS X to macOS.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The modern macFUSE consists of a closed-source kernel extension and three open-source userspace libraries: a fork of libfuse2, a fork of libfuse3 and an Objective-C framework for accessing macFUSE-specific functionality.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The last fully open-source release was OSXFUSE 3.8.3 of 2018.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] WinFsp is a userspace filesystem driver interface for Windows released under GPLv3.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] It implements the libfuse2 and libfuse3 C APIs in addition to its own APIs for C and .NET.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] OpenHarmony uses a fork of libfuse3 as a "third-party component" with minimal modification.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] It is unclear whether this inclusion is only for the Linux kernal-based branches of OpenHarmony (which would be trivial) or also for their custom LiteOS and UniProton kernels.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] To implement a new file system, a handler program linked to the supplied `libfuse` library needs to be written.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The main purpose of this program is to specify how the file system is to respond to read/write/stat requests.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The program is also used to mount the new file system.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] At the time the file system is mounted, the handler is registered with the kernel.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] If a user now issues read/write/stat requests for this newly mounted file system, the kernel forwards these IO-requests to the handler and then sends the handler's response back to the user.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] FUSE is particularly useful for writing virtual file systems.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] Unlike traditional file systems that essentially work with data on mass storage, virtual filesystems don't actually store data themselves.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] They act as a view or translation of an existing file system or storage device.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] In principle, any resource available to a FUSE implementation can be exported as a file system.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] The version of FUSE in Linux kernel includes various optional features that can be enabled to improve performance, including writeback (as opposed to write-through) caching and I/O passthrough.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] Conventional on-disk file systems can be implemented in user space with FUSE, e.g. for compatibility or licensing reasons.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] FUSE filesystems can create a view of an underlying file system, transforming the files in some way.
[src:virtual-file-system/filesystem-in-userspace] FUSE filesystems can expose the contents of archives or backup sets without having to first extract them.
