[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] A **virtual file system** (**VFS**) or **virtual filesystem switch** is an abstract layer on top of a more concrete file system.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] The purpose of a VFS is to allow client applications to access different types of concrete file systems in a uniform way.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] A VFS can, for example, be used to access local and network storage devices transparently without the client application noticing the difference.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] It can be used to bridge the differences in Windows, classic Mac OS/macOS and Unix filesystems, so that applications can access files on local file systems of those types without having to know what type of file system they are accessing.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] A VFS specifies an interface (or a "contract") between the kernel and a concrete file system.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Therefore, it is easy to add support for new file system types to the kernel simply by fulfilling the contract.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] One of the first virtual file system mechanisms on Unix-like systems was introduced by Sun Microsystems in SunOS 2.0 in 1985.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] It allowed Unix system calls to access local UFS file systems and remote NFS file systems transparently.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] For this reason, Unix vendors who licensed the NFS code from Sun often copied the design of Sun's VFS.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Other file systems could be plugged into it also: there was an implementation of the MS-DOS FAT file system developed at Sun that plugged into the SunOS VFS, although it was not shipped as a product until SunOS 4.1.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] The SunOS implementation was the basis of the VFS mechanism in System V Release 4.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] John Heidemann developed a *stacking* VFS under SunOS 4.0 for the experimental Ficus file system.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] This design provided for code reuse among file system types with differing but similar semantics (*e.g.*, an encrypting file system could reuse all of the naming and storage-management code of a non-encrypting file system).
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Heidemann adapted this work for use in 4.4BSD as a part of his thesis research; descendants of this code underpin the file system implementations in modern BSD derivatives including macOS.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Other Unix virtual file systems include the File System Switch in System V Release 3, the Generic File System in Ultrix, and the VFS in Linux.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] In OS/2 and Microsoft Windows, the virtual file system mechanism is called the Installable File System.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] The Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) mechanism allows userland code to plug into the virtual file system mechanism in Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OpenSolaris, and macOS.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] KIO and GVfs/GIO provide similar mechanisms in the KDE and GNOME desktop environments (respectively), with similar limitations, although they can be made to use FUSE techniques and therefore integrate smoothly into the system.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Sometimes Virtual File System refers to a file or a group of files (not necessarily inside a concrete file system) that acts as a manageable container which should provide the functionality of a concrete file system through the usage of software.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Examples of such containers are CBFS Connect from Callback Technologies or a single-file virtual file system in an emulator like PCTask or so-called WinUAE, Oracle's VirtualBox, Microsoft's Virtual PC, VMware.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] The primary benefit for this type of file system is that it is centralized and easy to remove.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Another major drawback is that performance is relatively low when compared to other virtual file systems.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Low performance is mostly due to the cost of shuffling virtual files when data is written or deleted from the virtual file system.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Direct examples of single-file virtual file systems include emulators, such as PCTask and WinUAE, which encapsulate not only the filesystem data but also emulated disk layout.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] This makes it easy to treat an OS installation like any other piece of software—transferring it with removable media or over the network.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] The Amiga emulator PCTask emulated an Intel PC 8088 based machine clocked at 4.77MHz (and later an 80486SX clocked at 25 MHz).
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] Users of PCTask could create a file of large size on the Amiga filesystem, and this file would be virtually accessed from the emulator as if it were a real PC Hard Disk.
[src:virtual-file-system/virtual-file-system] The UAE for Windows, WinUAE, allows for large single files on Windows to be treated as Amiga file systems.
